What if a pledged member is financially unable to have a full funeral and chooses cremation instead with a memorial service in the church?  Is this permissible? </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
First of all let me correct a misconception.  Pledging or paying has nothing to do with who is eligible for an Orthodox funeral in the church.  They must have received the sacraments of confession and communion within the past year even if they pledged or paid nothing.<br>
<br>
Expanding on what we've reviewed previously about cremation, the Orthodox Church holds the body in high regard, because our Lord and Savior Jesus Christ's body was buried and resurrected.  The end of an Orthodox Christian's life is a process, undergoing a series of prayers and services, inside and outside the church: prayers for healing, Holy Unction, prayers when illness increases, prayers at the departing of the soul from the body, prayers after the departing of the soul from the body, Trisagion prayers for the deceased, the funeral service, Trisagion prayers at the burial, memorial prayers on the 9th day, 40th day, and first annual anniversary.  And, in continuing memory of our departed, families remember them on the anniversaries of their deaths in the Divine Liturgy as we await the resurrection.<br>
<br>
One who is cremated is prohibited from having an Orthodox funeral service in the church.  There is no body remaining over which we can pray.  And, since the process outlined above has not been respected, why should their family desire a memorial service in the church?  We can pray for them as we do for all deceased, but a formal memorial service would be inconsistent with what they have done.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Fr. Nicon Patrinacos in A Dictionary of Greek Orthodoxy writes: A...the Orthodox teaching regarding the communion of the living and departed members of the Church should be kept in mind.  Believing that death is not the end but the beginning of a new life, the Church holds the position of a continuity of life from the moment of birth to the time of the Second Coming of the Lord.  Hence, the close bond of the Orthodox between the living and the dead expressed by memorial services, perpetual care of graves and the survival of the names of parents in the persons of grandchildren.  The Orthodox Liturgy is offered for the remission of sins of both living and dead, and the eternity it promises extends far beyond the grave not only in terms of time but in terms of the living of the dead in the memory and conscience of the Church.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Orthodox who contemplate cremation do so because of high costs resulting from a combination of funeral industry services, coffins, vaults, grave sites and the laws/regulations governing burial of the deceased.  The only remedy to reduce these costs would be to return to the Orthodox practice of no embalming and burial in a simple casket within twenty-four hours. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>©Very Rev. Fr. Olof Scott, Sunday Bulletin, October 5, 2003</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=t0mmyt>T0mmyT</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:green;><b>Mead Master<br>of the Grand Hooley<br>Cheeky Boy</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 397<br> <font color=#B87333>(11/4/03 3:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=54.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: an odd topic</span><hr size=1> I don't know for sure, but I had this idea that wakes may have originated once upon a time because they were burying 'dead' people alive.  Having a wake gave them enough time to make sure they were really dead.  Of course that was without the embalming process and all that.<br>
<br>
As far as cremation goes, the Catholic Church forbid it for a while due to the bodily resurrection and it is still forbidden only if it's done in defiance <p>“How can you claim to love a God you can’t see if you fail to love the brother or sister standing right in front of you?” – Mother Theresa</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=vonalbro>VONALBRO</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:navy;><b>Moderator and,<br>Lady of Good Cheer</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 478<br> <font color=#B87333>(11/5/03 2:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=54.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: an odd topic</span><hr size=1> Heartjoys,<br>
I'd have to echo TommyT's post above, there were people that were really alive, but were presumed dead and that is part of why the 'wake' was substantiated.  There is a lady on the net that loves little historical tidbits like this, I'll send her an e-mail and see if she has more on the subject.  You have to remember years and years ago there were no funeral homes and these 'wakes' happened at the homes of the people who died.  I know one of the subjects this lady posted about was even about tying little bells to the people who were buried to make sure they were dead, the bells remained tied to the person for several days after the funeral had taken place.  If the bell rang they knew to dig the person up.  Also, from memory, when it was too cold the burial couldn't take place right away here in the states at least.  It explained why some burial dates and actual death dates conflicted where geneology was concerned.  I was told this happened with my great-grandfather.  He was put in 'cold storage' until the ground thawed enough to bury him.  <br>
You mentioned the Jewish tradition of wrapping and using herbs and spices for burial, I'll try to look that up as well for you and see what I can come up with on it.  I found it interesting though that corpses didn't remain in the tomb but were put in estuary boxes eventually.  It may be though, that different areas came up with different ways of dealing with the dead, that would be my guess.<br>
<br>
God bless,<br>
Von <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jeffthefinn>jeffthefinn</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://webpages.charter.net/nilus/finnbutton.GIF" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:green;><b>Your Friendly<br>Orthodox Resource</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 178<br> <font color=#B87333>(11/5/03 2:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=54.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://webpages.charter.net/nilus/jfinn.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: an odd topic</span><hr size=1> The prohibition against cremation brings up another aspect of faith, that is relics of the saints.  In Orthodoxy the flesh itself can become deified and thus we have bodies that are incorrupt.  Biblically relics are attested to by the story found in 2 Kings 13:20-21<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>So Elisha died, and they buried him. Now bands of Moabites used to invade the land in the spring of the year. And as a man was being buried, behold, a marauding band was seen and the man was thrown into the grave of Elisha, and as soon as the man touched the bones of Elisha, he revived and stood on his feet.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
